text: Fire Extinguishers 1 Fire Extinguishers Introduction Fire is the result of a chemical combustion reaction. Four elements are necessary at all times for the reaction to continue—oxygen, fuel, heat, and an uninhibited chain reaction. The fire tetrahedron represents the addition of a component in the chemical chain reaction. Here’s how a fire develops: • The oxygen in the air is sufficient to support fire; • Some sort of fuel is required, such as wood, paper, or gasoline; • However, fuel does not

spontaneously ignite just because it is surrounded by oxygen. For the chemical combustion reaction to take place, the fuel must be heated to its ignition temperature by some outside source. The source of ignition might include a burning cigarette, overheating equipment, welding, static electricity, or a chemical reaction; • Once ignited, the heat of the flame keeps the fuel at the ignition temperature, so it will continue to burn as long as there are fuel and oxygen. This is called the

“uninhibited chain reaction.” Make sure you are aware of the possible sources of ignition in your facility. Classes of Fire Class A - fires involve ordinary combustible materials such as: - Wood, pallets, lumber - Plastic and foam - Paper and cardboard - Garbage Class B - fires involve flammable liquids such as: - Grease that is often found in the kitchen - Common solvents such as paint thinners, mineral spirits, and common organic solvents found in a laboratory - Gasoline, kerosene, and other

fuels - Oil and other combustible liquids Class C - fires involve energized electrical equipment such as: - Appliances, including stoves, washing machines, dryers - Switches, outlets, power cords, extension cords - Panel boxes and circuit breakers - Power tools, including drills, sanders, grinders, and saws. Class D - fires involve combustible metals such as: - Magnesium metals, chips, or grinding dusts that can be found in some metal shops. Fire Extinguishers 2 - Titanium metals, chips, or

grinding dusts that can be found in many aerospace sheet metal companies. - Potassium and sodium, which in their pure elemental forms are soft, ductile, malleable metals that can be easily cut with a knife or drawn into a wire. These metals are reactive toward air and water and are usually stored in a substance such as mineral oil. Extinguishing a potassium fire with water could result in an explosive reaction. - Finally, pyrophoric materials, which are highly reactive substances that are useful

in the synthesis of organic chemicals. Special training is required to store and handle these materials safely. Examples include alkyllithiums, alkylmagnesiums, and diphosphine. A Class D fire extinguisher readily available when handling these materials. An improper extinguisher could result in a larger fire—for example, a carbon dioxide extinguisher used on an alkylmagnesium fire would actually cause the fire to burn more intensely. Class K fires are kitchen fires. - This extinguisher is best

on fires involving cooking media such as fats, grease, and oils. Extinguishing the Fire Fire extinguishers are designed to remove at least one of the three elements (oxygen, fuel, heat) of the fire triangle so that a fire will die out. • The best way to remove heat from a fire is to dump water on the fire. This cools the fuel to below the ignition point, which interrupts the combustion cycle. • To remove oxygen, you can smother the fire so that it is not exposed to air. One way to smother a

small fire is to cover it with a heavy blanket. Another way is to dump nonflammable material on it, such as sand, baking soda, or inert gases. • Removing fuel is the most difficult approach to extinguishing the fire because fuels are everywhere. In most cases, the fuel will only be removed once the fire has burned it all up. Water Extinguishers • Water extinguishers are rated only for Class A fires, such as fires caused by wood, paper, plastic, and garbage. • Water extinguishers must not be used

on a Class B fire that involves burning flammable or combustible liquids. Oils, gasoline, solvents, and grease all float on water, so they will continue burning and actually spread out as they float on the water. A hot grease fire hit by a spray of cold water will result in the splattering of burning grease. • Spraying a normal water extinguisher on a Class C fire that consists of energized electrical equipment could result in an electrical shock. Fire Extinguishers 3 • The extremely hot

temperature of a Class D metal fire will break down the water molecules, or H20, into H2 and O2 molecules that will actually feed the fire and increase the intensity of the fire. Dry Chemical Extinguishers • They are your best all-around choice for the average industrial, manufacturing, office, or warehouse environment. • They have an advantage over carbon dioxide, or CO2, extinguishers in that they leave a blanket of nonflammable powder on the extinguished material, which reduces the likelihood

of reignition. • The disadvantage is that the powder makes a terrible mess that must be cleaned up. • Class BC-rated dry chemical extinguishers contain sodium bicarbonate, which is normal baking soda, or potassium bicarbonate, which is nearly identical to baking soda, as the extinguishing media and an inert compressed gas as the propellant. • Class ABC-rated dry chemical extinguishers are the most common. They contain ammonium phosphate as the extinguishing agent and an inert compressed gas as

the propellant. Carbon Dioxide or (CO2) Extinguishers As the CO2 escapes the extinguisher, it expands into a gas and cools the surrounding air, often forming ice around the extinguisher hose. CO2 extinguishes the fire by essentially displacing the oxygen near the fire, which smothers the fire and cools down the ignition source. In addition: • Carbon dioxide extinguishers are primarily effective on Class B—flammable liquid fires and Class C—electrical fires. • This extinguisher is not very

effective on Class A—normal combustible material—fires because the material will usually reignite. • Also, carbon dioxide should never be used on a Class D—metal—fire because it reacts with the burning metal and increases the fire. • The advantage of a CO2 extinguisher is that it does not leave any residue. • Because it does not leave a residue, CO2 is a good choice for fires that involve computer systems or delicate electronics. • A disadvantage of CO2 extinguishers is that the gas disperses

quickly, so they are only effective when used close to the fire at a distance of about 3 to 8 feet away. Metal/Sand Extinguishers • They are for flammable metal fires—Class D only. You should have approved Class D extinguishers if you are working with any type of flammable metal. Fire Extinguishers 4 • Powdered copper is preferred for fires that involve lithium and lithium alloys. It will cling to a vertical surface, making it the preferred agent for three-dimensional and flowing fires. • Sodium

chloride works well for metal fires involving magnesium, sodium, potassium, sodium potassium alloys, uranium, and powdered aluminum. • Finally, metal/sand extinguishers work when the extreme heat from the fire causes the extinguishing agent to cake and form a crust that excludes air and dissipates heat. Halon Extinguishers • Halon extinguishers contain a gas that interrupts the chemical reaction that takes place when fuels burn. • This extinguisher is only effective on Class B—flammable

liquids—and Class C— electrical—fires. • These extinguishers have been used to protect valuable electrical equipment since they leave no residue to clean up. • Because the gas quickly dissipates, they have a limited range of only 4 to 6 feet. • Halon 1211 production was banned by international agreement starting in 1994, therefore Halon extinguishers cannot be replaced. Also, maintaining a Halon extinguisher is expensive, because service companies must use a closed recovery system that prevents

the escape of Halon during maintenance. Halotron I Fire Extinguishers • Most extinguishers have been phased out and new production and serviceable units must use recycled or existing inventories of HCFC-123. • This chemical discharges as a liquid with high visibility. • It does not leave any residue. • Its nonconducting. • It’s ideal for computer rooms, clean rooms, telecommunications equipment, and electronics. • The extinguisher is rated for both Class B and Class C fires. FE-36 Extinguishers

• FE-36, stands for Hydrofluorocarbon-236fa or HFC-236fa, is a DuPont- manufactured Halon 1211 replacement. • It’s less toxic than Halon 1211 and Halotron I but still retains the same extinguishing properties. • It has zero ozone-depleting potential and is not scheduled to be phased out of production. Fire Extinguishers 5 • It’s rated for Class B and Class C fires and is especially useful for fires that involve expensive computer and electronic equipment. Water Mist Extinguishers • This type is

ideal for Class A fires where a potential Class C hazard exists. • The misting nozzle provides safety from potential electrical shock. • The misting nozzle also reduces the scattering of burning materials that can occur when using an ordinary water extinguisher. • Water mist extinguishers are an excellent choice for hospital environments, books, documents, and clean-room facilities. A non-magnetic version of the water mist extinguisher is the preferred choice for MRI, or magnetic resonance

imaging, and NMR, or nuclear magnetic resonance spectrometer, facilities. By this point we have covered the different types of fire extinguishers and what types of fires they are rated to fight. It is important for your safety to know which extinguisher to use for the types of fires you may face in your facility. Fight or Flight Decision Knowing which fire extinguisher should be used with each type of fire is the foundational knowledge needed to give you the ability to make a fight-or-flight

decision: Do you evacuate the facility or fight the fire with an extinguisher? Only attempt to use an extinguisher if you can say “yes” to every point that will be mentioned. If any of these conditions have not been met, do not fight the fire yourself—evacuate the area. • The fire alarm has been pulled, which means other employees are notified of the fire and are evacuating the building or coming to your aid. • Someone has actively dialed 911. • The fire is small, contained, and not spreading

beyond its starting point. • Smoke is minimal, non-toxic, and you can easily stay low to avoid the smoke while using the fire extinguisher. • The nearest exit is clear so that you can easily evacuate if the fire suddenly increases in size. When fighting a fire with an extinguisher, your back should always be toward the exit so you know that you can always escape. • A correct extinguisher for the type of fire is nearby. • And finally, you have been trained on how to properly use the extinguisher.

PASS Even though extinguishers come in a number of shapes and sizes, they all operate in a similar manner. To use an extinguisher, remember the acronym PASS, or P-A-S-S, which stands for Pull, Aim, Squeeze, and Sweep. Fire Extinguishers 6 • Pull the discharge locking pin at the top of the extinguisher. The pin keeps the handle from being accidentally pressed when the extinguisher is not in use. • Aim the discharge nozzle toward the base of the fire. Stand 8 to10 feet away from the fire. Note

that some types of extinguishers require you to be 6 feet or closer to the fire in order to be effective. • Squeeze the lever to discharge the extinguisher. When you release the handle lever, the discharge will stop. Keeping the lever squeezed will result in a continuous flow of extinguishing agent. Squeezing and releasing the lever will result in short bursts of extinguishing agent. • Sweep the nozzle back and forth toward the base of the fire. After the fire appears to be out, watch it

carefully, since it may reignite. Inspect Extinguishers • The fire extinguishers in your workplace need to be inspected at least once a month—more often in more severe work environments. • Make sure access to the extinguisher is not blocked by equipment, stock, or scrap. Coats, air hoses, or electrical cords must not be hanging on the extinguisher because that could prevent access in an emergency. • The pressure of the extinguisher must be at the recommended level. On extinguishers equipped with

a gauge, the needle should be in the green zone, which means that the pressure is not too high or too low. Replace the extinguisher if the pressure is not at the recommended level. • The pin and the tamperproof seal must be intact. The pin prevents the extinguisher from accidental discharge if the handle is bumped. The seal shows that the pin has not been removed and that the extinguisher is ready to use in an emergency. Replace the extinguisher if the pin or tamperproof seal are missing. •

Finally, be sure that the extinguisher does not have any dents, rust, chemical damage, or any other signs of abuse or wear. If you are responsible for inspecting extinguishers, make sure you use your facility’s inspection checklist and follow your facility’s inspection procedures. Care and Maintenance • Keep extinguishers clean. Wipe off any corrosive chemicals, oil, or grease that may have landed on the extinguisher. • Replace the extinguisher if it is damaged, dented, leaking, the pin is

missing or not sealed, the pressure is not correct, or if it has been discharged. Fire Extinguishers 7 • When an extinguisher is discharged, get it recharged immediately. If there is any delay, replace the extinguisher with a working one while the discharged one is waiting to be recharged. It is always good to have a few extra extinguishers in your workplace for this situation. • Fire extinguishers should undergo hydrostatic testing, or pressure testing, after a few years to ensure that the

cylinder is safe to use. Consult the owner’s manual, extinguisher label, or the manufacturer to see when your extinguishers need such testing. • Finally, non-rechargeable extinguishers must be removed from service 12 years from the date of manufacture. Locations and Signs Fire extinguisher regulations specify where extinguishers must be located and what types of signs must be used to point them out. Here’s what you need to know: • Extinguishers must be readily accessible without possibility of

injury. They cannot be blocked by equipment or materials and must be mounted in a way that they can easily be removed in an emergency. • Class A extinguishers cannot be located more than 75 feet from any point in the workplace. This measurement includes walking down aisles, around equipment, or around materials that might be in the way. • Class B extinguishers cannot be located more than 50 feet from any point in the workplace. • Class C extinguishers may be distributed in the same pattern that

you have for the Class A or Class B hazard, which is 50 to 75 feet. • Class D extinguishers must be no more than 75 feet from the hazard. • Portable fire extinguishers are mounted, located and identified so that they are readily accessible to employees without subjecting them to possible injury. Make sure you know where extinguishers are located in your facility as well as what extinguisher signage looks like in your workplace. Fire Extinguishers 8 Key Points to Remember The fire tetrahedron is

a great way to help remember that a fire needs oxygen, fuel, heat, and an uninhibited chain reaction to continue. • The fire hazard classes are: A—normal combustibles, B—flammable liquids, C— electrical, D—flammable metals, and K—kitchen. • Learn about the different types of extinguishers that are located in your workplace and know what classes of fire they are designed to extinguish. • Consider fight or flight based on these conditions before using an extinguisher on a fire: The alarm is
pulled; the fire department is called; the fire is small; there’s not much smoke; and the exit is clear. • And, to use an extinguisher, remember the acronym PASS.
